  Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink http://p.dw.com/p/2smwO Judicial and media reforms: A recent raft of judicial reforms has been criticized by Brussels and several European countries, who say it jeopardizes the independence of the judiciary. Warsaw insists the measures are needed to combat corruption. Poland faces disciplinary measures from Brussels if it does not scrap the reforms. WWII reparations: Last summer, politicians in Poland's ruling Law and Justice Party (PiS) accused Germany of shirking its responsibility for World War II and was mulling more reparations. Warsaw has since said then that the issue was not pressing, while Berlin maintains the issue has already been settled. Nord Stream 2: The Polish government also strongly objects to a proposed gas pipeline project that would link Russia to Germany and bypass Poland and Ukraine. Warsaw argues that the pipeline would make Europe more dependent on Moscow. Read more: Poles told to denounce 'anti-Polish' compatriots following Holocaust law What happens next: Morawiecki extended an invitation to Merkel for her to celebrations for Poland's 100th independence anniversary which will take place in November. rs/rt (AFP, dpa) Send  Facebook   Twitter   Google+   Whatsapp   
